title: No nonsense part cooler for FT5 Titan Volcano BLTouch combination

description.text:
NEW Version with shorter nozzles download the V7

With the close BLTouch mount, I needed a new compact partcooler for my volcano.
I want to use large nozzles and change nozzles quite often. The heater block should be accessible for a good grip. Cooler has to fit between BLTouch and Volcano.

This is the result. Design may still change a bit. I did already some tests with good results.
This is the latest version with some improvements : inclination of the outlets, fixation block more robust.

I used a special part to fix the cooler from this design

Added a 6th iteration :
Moved the fan inline with the nozzles to get a more equal airflow through both nozzles. cleaned up/streamlined the initial model a bit, changed the support to give more freedom for adjustment in Y-direction.
Made it a bit longer to the back. Space enough in the FT5.
Picture is still from a beta version

Normally I can keep the bed temperature at 75°C, with the first tests of this cooler I got a thermal runaway from the bed after switching to 100% from layer 20 on (6mm). Same fan.

Trick :
put a layer of adhesive aluminium tape on the side of the outlets facing the hot end. The PLA-testversion didn't even move/flex after printing 3 [email protected]°C.
Tape used for insulation purposes works great!

Tip : Use 3d-Tool to have a detailed look on this thing

description.text:
This is an all-in-one torture test. It is designed to test various aspects of your 3D printer, and has been in use at Quant 3D for a few years.

Most of the features are quite small, so you'll need to use your finest resolution.

Performance Areas Tested:

  1. Aspect Ratio
  2. Wall Thickness
  3. Controlled Cuts (Horizontal and Vertical)
  4. Metric Threads (male & female) (M4, M6, M8, M10)
  5. Twists and Tapers
  6. Textures
  7. Latticework
  8. Spiral "S" - curvilinear interpolation
  9. Wrapped Cylinder - circular interpolation and holes in thin walled vertical surface
  10. Ball in Cage - Spherical objects (especially at the support/model interface)
  11. Oblique Angles - bent columns should have constant thickness
  12. Tight Spaces (Onion)
  13. Text on flat surfaces
  14. Thin Overhangs
  15. Cones
  16. Subresolution grid
  17. Undercuts
  18. Overhangs - 5° to 85°.
  19. Quant 3D logo - support material interfacing, texture quality, text curve quality
  20. Freeform Triangle Pocket
  21. Spiral on underside - spiral interpolation, thin walls and support

Printer:

Quant 3D

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

Since this is a test piece, feel free to play with your printer's settings and adjust accordingly. Most of the features will not print correctly unless your layer height is at most 0.200mm.
Reducing the scale is not recommended.

Also - the STL orientation is goofy. It is designed to print laying flat, as shown in the pictures.

description.text:
On a random journey through designs, I happened upon the Toothpaste Transfer tool. Unfortunately, there's just no consistency out there in thread design and the tool didn't fit my specific need; no amount of scaling would work. What I really needed was a generic tool to patch any two different screw threads together.

So, based on that original requirement of refilling a toothpaste tube, here we have a tool for connecting any two screw sizes you might need to connect. It's a basic thread design, and I've kept complexity out of it by sticking with the self-proclaimed "poor man's screw library", which I learned a little about how to use from another look through the Nut Job.

This design then requires you to take a few measurements from each of your thread. You need to outer diameter of the threads, the distance between two threads, and the length of thread required. Feed that into the tabs for Screw 1 and Screw 2 and you'll be ready to go. If the two sizes are wildly different, you're possibly going to end up with some tough-to-print geometry, so you can then adjust the connector piece to work with your printer's capabilities. If your threads are of the typical type seen on plastic bottles these days, add 1m to your screw diameter to take account of the sharp edge they've shaved off.

I'll be fascinated to see what kind of whacky connectors people create with this. If you do find it useful, please consider naming your remix well and maybe taking a picture of the final printed object with it's intended use.

Incidentally, the default values selected fit two UK Colgate Toothpaste tubes.

comments.text: The model already adds 1mm to the measurement in order to allow the screw to work. Are you calipers digital? Are you measuring down to the tenth? If you have analogue calipers and are already measuring down to the tenth, the only thing I can suggest is to add an additional amount to allow for printer accuracy. Certainly, other ways to throw things out would be a compacted first layer, or using a different nozzle size, which could further affect tolerance. How long is the thread you're making? I'm curious also what you're trying to make a thread for in case I could also take measurements and try the same thing?

I wanted to make a connector so I can easily pour the contents from one bottle into the other.  I like this idea better than using a funnel because I don't have to worry about the bottle falling out of the funnel.

comments.text: I think the issue comes from the complexity of the geometry generated from the screw library that I re-used. This accounts for both the poor performance and also the error message you see. In neither case is this a problem, but it does slow things down. In fact, you'll most likely find that a render results in better performance of the model when you rotate it than a preview. I appreciate that a render takes longer, but this is a result of OpenSCAD performance. In any case, as long as you can render and export, rotation around the model is mostly irrelevant. The digital calipers are possibly the source of the measurement issues, unless you've paid a vast sum for something truly "professional". My digital calipers are off and need resetting to zero regularly.
comments.author: wolf9545

comments.text: Thank you for your help.  I will have to play around with the settings.  I think I am just not adding enough onto the measurements that I am using.  I did print out a calibration cube a long time ago and it did measure out to the 20mm; give or take a few 0.05mm.  I might just have to add a little bit more in both the opening and the thread pitch.  I can get it to screw on but it is a tight fit.
comments.author: SpoonUnit

comments.text: I just had another thought too. Very possibly you don't have a "typical" screw thread here. This model makes screw threads, and your typical modern commercial product in a plastic tub isn't using screw threads, but a thread shape modeled specifically for performance with plastics. This would require more modelling to get the right thread and I think it could well make it challenging to print the thread at both ends, as I think you'll notice the thread would print better in one orientation than the other. I also printed something like this, and it's also extremely tight if I try to do it all the way up, but the first rotation works fine, so if this is also the case for you, perhaps try a shorter thread instead of trying to go all the way.

I used the design of the intake fan for 120mm adapter from the below link to screw into. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1373892

6-32 screws --> length 1 1/4inch
M4 nuts

6-32 screws --> length 3/4inch
I also used rubber washers to help protect the hard drive vibration.

I have used this for about a month and it worked perfectly!

description.text:
It's based on a 3D version of turtle algorithm. If you are using OpenSCAD and need a library of turtle graphics 3D, the code I wrote may be a reference.

Can STLs here be printed? It may be hard for a FDM printer but easier for other types, such as those using a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed layer by layer.

If you are still sticking to a FDM printer, challenging a version with fewer recursions would be a good start. In the customizer, recursions are limited by init_leng, leng_limit and leng_scale parameters.

More recursions require more time to generate a preview in the customizer so the preview may be terminated by a browser due to security issues. If that's so, download the .scad and use OpenSCAD directly.

Someone said if all branches' overhang angles were under 90 degrees, it's possible for DLPs to print it. I upload one for this. If you have a DLP, give it a try. :)

title: 60, 80, 120 mm fan cover/duct with 90 degree deflector

description.text:
This is a general purpose fan duct that can be used with any 60mm fan (with 50mm mounting hole spacing). The fan is designed to redirect the air flow at a 90 degree angle.

1/2/2017 - By request, I added an 80mm version also. Scaling up the 60 to 80 is not an option, because hole spacing changes by a different ratio.

8/18/2017 - Added 120mm, and 120mm Slim (3/4 height) versions.\

8/23/2017 - Corrected the hole spacing on the 80mm version. Now is 72mm, was 68. (center to center)

I designed this specifically to improve my anet a8 printer. When mounted in conjunction with a 40mm board cover (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1803120) and a fan size adapter (60to40.stl - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21112), the single 60mm fan will cool BOTH the main board AND the x axis motor. See photo.

Please check out my new product: The "OFFi" Auto-off switch for ANET A8 at: http://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_nkw=jimb15122

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.18

Infill:

10%

Notes:

I printed this with a 12mm brim, and heated glass bed, with light hairspray. Let cool fully before detaching. Use minimal supports.

After printing the board cover, just clip away the built in fan guard for the original 40mm fan.

I secured the cover to the board with a large cable tie after simply slipping the mounting posts over the exposed screw threads. You may need to reverse the screws so the heads are facing inward.

Mount the fan either blowing away or toward the board. I think towards the board is better, as the air stream is better diffused.

Verify there is enough clearance to permit the x motor to move along the z axis.

Use large cable tie to secure the entire assembly

This is the first of what I hope to be many annual Christmas Tree Ornaments I design and print on my 3D printer. This depicts an Afinia H479 (or Up!) printer, having just completed a Santa Hat.  
UPDATED December 13, 2014 - I was asked if I could remove the date, which makes total sense, so I did. The file Printer_NO_DATE_Green.stl is the printer without the dents to insert the date. (This was originally designed as a 2013 Christmas ornament, so the file with the date indentations is still available, but for those who just want to print an Afinia printer, this is the file for you.)

This is a 1/4 scale model of an Afinia H-479 printer with some of the pertinent detail in place. (There are no ports on the back, and no body screws.) Print the pieces in the orientation of the files (or don't. That's up to you, it should print fairly well anyway) and glue them however youlike. I used Krazy glue on this one which seems quite sturdy. There is a hole at the top left for a screw eye (or I found a small cotter pin works better, cut down to about .8cm in length and Krazy-glued in place) which will allow you to hang it on a tree using string, ribbon or a wire ornament hanger.

  • First, glue the Z-Axis motor to the Z-Axis arm (underneath in back.)

  • Then glue the groove under the Z-Axis arm to the printer body where the lower ridges meet the main Y-Axis arm.

  • Glue the bed heater to the underneath of the plate

  • Glue the plate to the Z-Axis arm

  • Glue the LED into the small hole at front left

  • Glue the Initialize switch to the rectangular hole next to it

  • Glue the three warning labels into the triangluar shaped grooves

  • Glue the spool holder to the Y-Axis arm side

  • Place the filmanet onto one of the central cylinders of the spool parts, then glue the two spool parts together.

  • If this is intended as a standing prop, you can feel free to leave the spool loose. However as a tree decoration it is better glued to the spool holder.

  • Glue the tassle to the hat, the hat to the fringe, and glue the fringe down to the print plate (again, if this is intended as a standing prop or toy, you don't have to glue the hat to the bed.)

  • Glue the numerals in place

  • Hang your ornament. (Or place it on your GI Joe's desk, or your American Girl's workbench, or Barbie's table, or do what you like with it.

  • Except don't sell it. If you wish to market it, I wanna cut! :-)

description.text:
The base of this design in really cool to me. I feel it to be a nice base for adjustment. There is a lot of room to add other things. It still has a nice form factor and sits well on a table or in a lap. If anything I just wanted to make it easier to adjust and open up all the ports. I took the .STL files and imported into SketchUp. It took me a few hours to clean up the extraneous line created from the import. Then it was just a bit of trial and error. I will include the source files when I feel it is done. The yellow header will be gone at that time. ;)

New Parts:

Button: https://www.adafruit.com/products/917
Speaker: http://amzn.to/2hgUjhd
Heatsink : https://www.adafruit.com/products/3082
2x - Adafruit Power Boost 1000c: https://www.adafruit.com/products/2465
2x - Lithium Ion Polymer Battery - 3.7v 4400mAh: https://www.adafruit.com/products/354

Screws:

2x - M2.5 x .45 x 6M
6x - M3 x .5 x 6M
8x - M3 x .5 x 10M

Changes:
  1. Lid has was made taller. This gives a lip around the screen. In case of a fall, the edge of the case should take the impact.
  2. Lid was given a cutout to accommodate the ribbon cables for the inset edge made in #1.
  3. All ports made accessible.
  4. Moved raspberry pi towards the wall to line up ports closer to the outside edge.

title: Phoenix v2 Silicone Overmolding + string tensioner

description.text:
Male fingertips for phoenix_v2 ... female moulds. Print both same size, dollop of 2-part silicone in the female (helps to fill the through-hole of the male part with silicone too), 'click' the male fingertip into the female. Should demould cleanly and trim with a knife. Because of the tiny amount of silicone used this is way cheaper than 'tippies' even if you printed dozens of replacement fingertips. Looks better too,

I have non-string-winder versions tucked away too if anyone doesn't want the string-tensioner.

To use the tensioner, attach the string to part1, insert the part2 in the string winder hole, insert a small screwdriver and tension to the desired tension. click it in and hold, and remove the screwdriver, and insert part2 firmly until it's flush (will probably need pliars).

You'll want to be careful with your external perimeter width (print externals first, use a single thick external perimeter)... because of the small size it's pretty important to have good clean well-dimensioned prints to get all these parts to snap together nicely. I have a spreadsheet of the settings I wound up using if people have trouble printing these.

comments.text: I used standard silicone rubber moulding rubber with food grade catalyst since it's likely to be near people's food at some point.

description.text:
An entry for the remix challenge that is sure to warm the heart of a loved one in the winter.
For those that live in the cold temperatures and have that white fluffy stuff, you can create a heart shaped snow ball and leave one or many around the yard, on the car, or even making a path.

Included is a special insert and an additional mold half that allows for the special inset with an additional message.(not to be thrown!!)

Designed to take full advantage of the 200 x 200 of a Prusa i3, you can scale the size to 50% - 60% for a more manageable sized heart snow ball.

Models were created in Wings3D and Blender. I am still learning to use blender and like the ease of modeling in Wings3D

Disclaimer: Throwing snow balls at loved ones does not always warm their hearts as stated above. Use as a snowball at your own risk..

More images of final prints to follow.

Inspiration

The inspiration comes from the snowman maker and the a desire to create something for my wife for our 17th anniversary, which is the end of December. She is always leaving messages in the snow for me, and this will be my turn to leave a special message for her.

Update #1

Updated the Mold_Bottom-W_Insert to better fit the Insert.
After printing the mold bottom I found that the insert did not fit well and this is when I remembered one of the rules of designing parts that fit together. Don't try to have a perfect fit if one is not needed.... Not sure why I did not design the models this way in the first place.
Working on the mold bottom a second time for images. I will updated when finished.

This is a stand for a standard 2.5" Hard Drive with USB3.0 to SATA adapter.

I had an old Seagate (don't really like Seagate) Laptop Hard Drive laying around from my Sister-in-Law's laptop, HP (don't really like HP) that crapped out due to bad/cold solder joints on the CPU (A common program, I came to discover, for that model).

Well, Windows 10 Backup to a NAS (Network Attached Storeage) fails for me after about a 1 week. Don't know why. Had to reset the backup three times over the course of a couple months before I gave up.

So I decided to put that old Seagate HD to use as my backup drive. And I need a case for it.

Bought a used Seagate USB3.0 to SATA adapter for it so I could just plug it right into my laptop and backup to it (turns out you need a VERY short USB3.0 cable otherwise there's just not enough power to keep the HD going during the backup...)

I designed this case around those specs, so I'm not sure if it will work with any other Drive/Adapter combo.

Just for fun, I designed this to be printed in 'Vase' mode (Spiralized) so it would have very thin walls. Plus I used Translucent Blue, so I can see all the goodies inside (and the blinky light when its running).

You can still print this solid if you wish....

title: Breadboard Spring Vise Full Size in Two Pieces

description.text:
My large Printrbot is... um.... let's just say inaccessible for the moment. My Monoprice Mini Select isn't large enough to print the full baseboard. So I cut it in half with some alignment holes. You probably don't have to glue them together, but you can. With a breadboard rubberbanded in place, the two pieces stay together well enough.

I print in PETG on a heated piece of BuildTak so I didn't bother putting the anti-curl disks at the edges. Would probably print well in PLA too. If you use ABS you might want to put the disk back at the other side.

Note you need the original STLs to get the OpenSCAD program to work. Also--probably obvious--but you need to print 4 of the "jaws" from the original. The jaws on one side counterbalance the ones on the other side with rubber bands between them.

So go to the original source to get those and the baseplate STL if you want to regenerate it.

Note the alignment slot is about 1mm larger than the alignment tabs. That way if you are overextruding, you get a little play.
